In this section you will be asked a series of simple questions that will help determine the exposure you might have had to the virus.
Based on your answers, you will be assigned a color code that represents the risk level that you have and hence the actions that you should take to look after yourself as well as others.
Your information is extremely valuable and together with that of many others will help us win the battle over COVID-19.

You can re-take the asssessment for 2 reasons:
1. If you feel like your results are incorrect \n\n2. It’s been over 7 days since your last assessment, and you are required to re-take the assessment.
If you feel like your results need to be fixed, you can retake the self-assessment.
Based on your answers, you are at a lower risk of contracting COVID-19.
Based on your answers, you are at a higher risk of contracting COVID-19 and we recommend speaking to a medical professional about getting tested.
Based on your self-assessment answers, you are at a higher risk of contracting COVID-19 and we recommend speaking to Health Services about getting tested.
Here are some steps to help you continue to protect yourself:

Your results confirm that you have tested positive for COVID-19.\n\nWhile this is likely to be a very worrying time for you and your family, by following the steps below you will find it easier to cope with the quarantine phase and will protect yourself and others.

Your results confirm that you have tested negative for COVID-19.\n\nFor the safety of yourself and others, you are still advised to adopt self quarantine measures. This will allow us to continue to monitor your health and any change in symptoms.
Ensure you are isolating yourself from others. By doing so, you can slow the spread of COVID-19 and protect your family, friends and community.
Contact Estijaba Hotline as soon as possible, and our team will be happy to assist you around testing recommendations and next steps.
1. Anticipate at least 14 days in isolation at home.
2. Make sure you have enough of any prescription and non-prescription medication you need to last a couple of weeks.
3. Make sure there is availability of a single room and private bathroom within your home.
4. Make sure you have access to communication (including phone and/or data) for monitoring by health workers, reporting a change in symptoms and accessing services.
\n\nFor the full home quarantine guidelines, please click here.
Please call the number below as soon as possible, and our team will be happy to assist you around testing recommendations and next steps.
Clean your hands regularly and thoroughly with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
Maintain at least 2 meter distance between yourself and anyone who is coughing or sneezing.
Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed / sanitized hands
For your safety and the safety of your loved ones, please stay #TogetherAtHome
